<div itemprop="articleBody">
<h2>Tutorial 13. Sewing the Corset in the Throw-Over Technique. </h2>
<p></p>
<p><strong>I continue joining the pieces of the corset. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I take the side back piece and sew it to the ready half of the corset front, i.e. to the side front piece. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I start it by attaching the lace layer of the side back piece. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image002.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>And then I turn the piece over and join the organza layers. </strong>Please note that I am not making any bar-tacks either at the beginning or at the end of the seam. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image004.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I topstitch the seam allowance. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image006.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong>And then I trim the seam allowance and sew a bone onto it. </strong>Be careful not to let the edge of the bone go beyond the princess seam that joins the pieces. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image008.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image010.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image012.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image014.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p></p>
<p><strong>There is only one piece left unattached - the central back piece. I have decided to join the organza layers first and the lace afterwards. </strong></p>
<p></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image016.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image018.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image020.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image022.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image024.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image026.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image028.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p></p>
<p><strong>Here is the first half of our corset. </strong></p>
<p><strong>You can stitch along the top edge to secure the lace but you shouldn’t do it at the bottom. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image030.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>And then I sew the second half of the corset following exactly the same procedure. I start from encasing a bone in fabric and then I join all pieces starting from the central front one and gradually moving to the centre of the back. </strong></p>
<p>As you can see now, the throw-over technique is not that difficult but very helpful. It is rather widely used and comes in handy in many cases when traditional ways of decorating a corset are impossible to apply. It also creates an illusion that your corset is covered with a smooth whole piece of lace. </p>
<p><strong>Now after all pieces have been sewn together, we can start finishing the bottom of the corset. </strong></p>
<p><strong>You should stitch two parallel bones onto the spot where a lacing bar will be located. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image032.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image034.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p></p>
<p><strong>I try to stitch them on edge-to-edge, as close to each other as possible. A small gap is still always there, about 1mm or even less. </strong></p>
<p></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image036.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image038.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p></p>
<p><strong>I cut the bone (purely instinctively for now). I am going to slightly even out the length of the back later. </strong></p>
<p></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image040.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong>What we have is a corset body that’s fully covered with lace and has inner bones sewn to it. </strong>There is an individual bone over each princess seam that will also serve as a tunnel for inserting plastic bones to strengthen the corset. </p>
<p><strong>I sew a straight narrow Rigilene bone onto the cut edge of the central front piece. </strong>I try my best to sew it on at the very edge. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image042.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I secure it with the second parallel stitch </strong>and cut it up instinctively. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image044.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>And now I need to even out the outer edge of the front </strong>and remove any organza or lace sticking out from it and going beyond the edge of the bone. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image046.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>A half of our corset sewn in the throw-over technique looks like this: </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2013_files/image048.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>

</div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody -->
